## About GitLab Migrator CLI App
This is a command-line tool for Windows / Linux, with which we can migrate a GitLab Cloud repository to a self hosted GitLab server using a set of commands which we can also try to automate using .batch / .sh files

## What is GitLab Cloud Server?
The computer / server that is running behind the domain name https://gitlab.com is referred as GitLab Cloud Server. Any user can create an account and use the features offered by the server. GitLab is a SCM tool which comes with Issue tracking, CI/CD, Wiki and other such features.

## What is a self-hosted GitLab instance?
A self-hosted GitLab instance refers to a computer / server in which we have installed GitLab software so that we can use the computer / server to host our repository and use it as SCM tool. This is done for security purposes so that we have our repository secure in our premises.

## What is the use of this App?
We can use this app to automate the process of migrating our repositories from GitLab cloud to our self-hosted GitLab server. Also, this app automatically migrates the following that were previously need to be manually created in the instance.
- Users
- Branch Protections
- Integrations (say Jira, Teams etc., )
- Smart Commits (Jira Issue IDs, GitLab Issue ID etc.,)

## What are the configurations required?
1. **Source URL**: This is the URL of the GitLab Cloud Instance. This is usually https://gitlab.com/api/v4/, but anyways we can change it if we want to migrate from some other server to our server. Please append "api/v4/" to end of the URL. 
2. **Source PAT(Personal Access Token)**: This is the Personal Access Token generated by the user who is the admin of the server and also admin of the group / project  as the case may be.
3. **Destination URL:** This is the URL of the self hosted GitLab server. Please append "api/v4/" to end of the URL. 
4. **Destination PAT(Personal Access Token)**: This is the Personal Access Token generated by the user who is the admin of the self-hosted server. We need to manually create a admin user for this purpose. 
5. **Group Folder Location:** This is the location of the folder in which all group export bundles will be saved for import purposes.
6. **Project Folder Location:** This is the location of the folder in which all project export bundles will be saved for import purposes.
7. **Shell Executable:** This is the path to the shell executable in which shell files can be run. Commit-rewriting feature of the app requires this to function. We could use 'gitBash.exe' for this purpose

# ==Individual Process Commands==
- ### glm initiate-export group `<groupID>`
	This command initiates export of a group from the GitLab Cloud Server. After this, a download-link will be sent to the email ID of the admin. Only after receiving the mail, we can then download the group's export bundle. The link will be only active for 24 hours

- ### glm initiate-export project `<projectID>`
	This command initiates export of a project from the GitLab Cloud Server. After this, a download-link will be sent to the email ID of the admin. Only after receiving the mail, we can then download the project's export bundle. The link will be only active for 24 hours

- ### glm download-export group `<groupID>`
	This command downloads the export bundle of a group from the download-link that was sent to the admin's email to the location set in configuration.

- ### glm download-export project `<projectID>`
	This command downloads the export bundle of a project from the download-link that was sent to the admin's email to the location set in configuration.

- ### glm import group `<groupID>`
	This command imports the group into the destination server with the help of the group export bundle that was downloaded previously.

- ### glm import project `<groupID>` `<projectID>`
	This command imports the project into the destination server with the help of the project export bundle that was downloaded previously. GroupID is required to get the namespace of the project

- ### glm list-users group `<groupID>`
	This command lists all the users who directly belong to the group from the GitLab Cloud

- ### glm list-users project `<projectID>`
	This command lists all the users who directly belong to the project from the GitLab Cloud

- ### glm list-subgroups `<groupID>`
	This command lists all subgroups that belong to the group from GitLab Cloud

- ### glm migrate-members `<groupID>`
	This command gets all direct and indirect members(subgroup / project) who all belong to the group of GitLab Cloud server and their details and adds them all to the self hosted GitLab server.

- ### glm fix-integrations
	This command creates any left-over integrations to the self hosted server which weren't added to the project during import time.  

- ### glm rewrite-commit `<groupID>` `<projectID>`
	This command takes in groupID and projectID of the self-hosted server which needs commit-rewriting. This command should be used if we have non working smart commits. Otherwise, this command needn't be used

# ==Bulk Process Commands==
- ### glm initiate-bulk-export `<groupID>`
	This command migrates users and initiates export of a group and all its projects from the GitLab Cloud Server. After this, download-links will be sent to the email ID of the admin. Only after receiving the mail, we can then download the export bundles. The links will be only active for 24 hours. 

- ### glm initiate-bulk-export `<groupID>` only `<projectIDs...>`
	This command migrates users and initiates export of a group and only its projects that are mentioned. After this, download-links will be sent to the email ID of the admin. Only after receiving the mail, we can then download the export bundles. The links will be only active for 24 hours.

- ### glm initiate-bulk-export `<groupID>` except `<projectIDs...>`
	This command migrates users and initiates export of a group and all its projects except the ones that are mentioned. After this, download-links will be sent to the email ID of the admin. Only after receiving the mail, we can then download the export bundles. The links will be only active for 24 hours.

- ### glm bulk-migrate `<groupID>` 
	This command downloads and imports the group and all its projects under it one by one. Please note that we can only import a project every 1 minute, not faster than that. All downloads are as usual saved to the location set in configuration.

- ### glm bulk-migrate `<groupID>` only `<projectIDs...>`
	This command downloads and imports the group and only the projects that are mentioned one by one. Please note that we can only import a project every 1 minute, not faster than that. All downloads are as usual saved to the location set in configuration.

- ### glm bulk-migrate `<groupID>` except `<projectIDs...>`
	This command downloads and imports the group and all the projects except the ones that are mentioned one by one. Please note that we can only import a project every 1 minute, not faster than that. All downloads are as usual saved to the location set in configuration.
